### **Goal of this lesson:**

Open RStudio, create an R Markdown file, run your **first line of R code**, and load a simple Excel dataset. Before you start, make sure to download these two excel files to your Desktop.

### Data Sets Needed

#### [Exam Data 1](https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1uAl3m6RqnKNELm33y2S5z-TC5vN6AyKQ/edit?gid=2056008568#gid=2056008568)

#### [Exam Data 2](https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1uAl3m6RqnKNELm33y2S5z-TC5vN6AyKQ/edit?usp=sharing&ouid=116572267343073467545&rtpof=true&sd=true)

## **Step 1: Open RStudio**

-   Open **RStudio** (not just R)

-   You should see **four panes** (Console, Environment, Files/Plots/Help, Editor)

    -   If you only see one pane, that’s okay — it will change in the next step

------------------------------------------------------------------------

## **Step 2: Create a New R Markdown File**

1.  In the top menu, click:\
    **File → New File → R Markdown…**

2.  In the pop-up window:

    -   **Title:** Lesson 1\

    -   **Author:** your name\

    -   **Output format:** HTML

![](data:image/png;base64,)

3.  Click **OK**
4.  Click File \> Save As \> “Lesson1.Rmd”
5.  You will see something like this: 

![](images/clipboard-2788188984.png)

## **Step 3: Write Your First Line of Code!**

-   Highlight everything under the initial title and delete it:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

-   Click the Green C button with a + sign and select R

![](data:image/png;base64,)\
\

-   A new “code chunk” will appear! 

![](data:image/png;base64,)\
\

-   Inside the “code chunk” copy and paste the code below: 

``` r
# Set working directory to Desktop
setwd(“~/Desktop”)

# Confirm R can see your files
getwd()
list.files()
# Load the package for reading Excel files
library(readxl)

# Read the Excel file
exam <- read_excel(“ExamData_Original_FAKE.xlsx”)

# Preview the data
head(exam)
```
